A virtual environment (venv) is an isolated Python workspace where you can install packages specific to a project without affecting:

The system-wide Python installation
Other projects
OS dependencies (important for Linux/AIX servers)

Think of it like a sandbox for your project.

Why Is a Virtual Environment Important?
✔ 1. Avoids Package Conflicts
Different projects may need different versions of the same Python library.
Example:

Script A needs paramiko 3.x
Script B needs paramiko 2.x

A virtual environment keeps them separate.

✔ 2. Protects System Python
Linux & AIX rely on system Python for internal tools.
If you install or update packages globally using pip, you can break OS-level utilities.
Using venv ensures system Python remains untouched.

✔ 3. Cleaner Project Management
Every automation script/project has its own dependencies, documented in:
requirements.txt

This makes your automation easy to:

Reproduce
Share
Deploy


✔ 4. Safe for Servers
On production servers, you usually don't want to install libraries globally.
Virtual environments let you deploy Python automation without risk.

### How to crate virtual enviornement 


python3 -m venv venv
source venv/bin/activate

pip install paramiko
pip install psutil
pip freeze > requirements.txt

python healthcheck.py
deactivate
